</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="268" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="7.[1443,2655,292,765]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1444,1682,292,325]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Painted Treeshrews spend most of their time on the ground. Like most treeshrews, the Painted Treeshrew is diurnal and leave their nests at 06:30-06:45 h and return at 16:20-17:58 h. Males can be active for more hours during the day than females, but conclusions were based on very few individuals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="268" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[1443,2655,292,765]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1445,2137,449,482]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
Home ranges of Painted Treeshrews average just over 9 ha. Males appear to have larger home ranges than females. Nest sites are more commonly found on the ground.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="268" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="7.[1443,2655,292,765]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1445,1791,568,601]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
CITES Appendix II. Classified as Least Concern on The [UCN Red List. The Painted Treeshrew is relatively widely distributed on Borneo. Nevertheless, its population is declining but not at a rate that would warrant listing in a threatened category.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
